\par Bayesian modelling approaches are well-suited to address the complexity and incomplete nature of many conservation datasets, given their flexibility and power to provide robust estimates under a wide range of conditions (e.g., Case Study 1). Bayesian models can be specified to include a wide range of data distributions via ready-to-use packages in programs like R (e.g., `brms'), and expanded to infinite  model specifications. Multiple sources and types of data can be amalgamated into Bayesian Belief Networks \citep{marcot2001using,newton2007bayesian}, and extant information can be used to inform `prior distributions' used in Bayesian modelling \citep{o2008informed,mcneish2016using}. (For more on what `prior distributions' or `priors' are, see Box 1.) As such, Bayesian methods can enable, social, biological, and physical data to be used to inform conservation decisions. 
